â­ Recommended: NFS Export

Here is the exact setup to export /mnt/media-local via NFS from Proxmox â†’ mount on Mint.

ğŸ”§ STEP 1 â€” Install NFS server on Proxmox

Run on Proxmox:

apt update
apt install nfs-kernel-server -y

ğŸ”§ STEP 2 â€” Create an export entry

Edit /etc/exports:

nano /etc/exports


Add this line (replace your LAN subnet if needed):

/mnt/media-local 192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check,no_root_squash)


Explanation:

rw = read/write

sync = safe writes

no_subtree_check = required for stability

no_root_squash = lets Mint root account write properly

Save & exit.

ğŸ”§ STEP 3 â€” Apply the export rules
exportfs -arv
systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server


Check:

exportfs -v


You should now see /mnt/media-local exported.

ğŸ”§ STEP 4 â€” Mount the share on Linux Mint

First, install NFS client:

sudo apt install nfs-common -y


Create a mount point:

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/proxmox-media


Now mount:

sudo mount -t nfs nj-proxmox-01:/mnt/media-local /mnt/proxmox-media


Replace nj-proxmox-01 with your Proxmox IP address if needed (ex: 192.168.1.50).

Verify:

df -h /mnt/proxmox-media


You should now see the 62.7T share from Proxmox.

ğŸ”§ STEP 5 â€” Make the mount persistent on Mint

Edit fstab:

sudo nano /etc/fstab


Add:

nj-proxmox-01:/mnt/media-local  /mnt/proxmox-media  nfs  defaults  0  0


or (better performance + stability):

nj-proxmox-01:/mnt/media-local  /mnt/proxmox-media  nfs  rw,noatime,hard,intr  0  0


Save â†’ exit.

Test:

sudo mount -a